[normal]In this evidence, I conc
[normal]entrate 
[normal]largely on issues raised by 
[normal]questions 3, 4 and 5. 
[normal]By way of introduction, I wish to state that the
[normal] move to a codified constitution would not necessarily trigger a change in the
[normal] role of the
[normal] Britis
[normal]h
[normal] judiciary
[normal]. 
[normal]I
[normal]t would be
[normal] possible
[normal] to draft the provisions of the new constitution and
[normal] ensure that the judiciary 
[normal]has 
[normal]the same attributions and the same constit
[normal]utional position therein
[normal]. 
[normal]For the role o
[normal]f the judiciary to change following the adoption of the 
[normal]codified constitution
[normal], i
[normal]t would mean
[normal] one of two things: 
[normal]either
[normal] 
[normal]the authors
[normal] of
[normal] the 
[normal]constitution took a decision
[normal] to alter
[normal] the role of the judiciary in the new
[normal] document or
[normal] despite
[normal] the
[normal] lack of formal change
[normal], the ‘codified’
[normal] constitutional environment trigger
[normal]ed
[normal] 
[normal]new political and/or judicial practices and an unforeseen
[normal] transformation of
[normal] the role and position of the judiciary.
[normal] If the
[normal] second
[normal] situation
[normal] 
[normal]requires a certain degree of ball gazing
[normal], it is important to no
[normal]te that this evolution is
[normal] possible
[normal]; new constitutiona
[normal]l settlements have been known to trigger dynamics of constitutional change over and beyond the strict text of the constitution
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]here are plenty of 
[normal]comparative 
[normal]instances around the world of courts transforming their role and position
[normal] beyond the ones contai
[normal]ned
[normal] in the constitutional document
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]While the move to a codified constituti
[normal]on would not necessarily change
[normal] the role of the judiciary
[normal] in itself
[normal], the adoption of a system of constitutional review has the
[normal] potential to do so. In fact
[normal], t
[normal]he adopti
[normal]on of such a
[normal] system raises such fundamental questions
[normal] for the British constitution
[normal] that it would likely transform
[normal] it entirely. 
[normal]Already 
[normal]in the last decade, 
[normal]s
[normal]eeds of this
[normal] transformation
[normal] have
[normal] be
[normal]en
[normal] sown
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]and the
[normal] adoption of a system of constitutional
[normal] review would h
[normal]ave th
[normal]e effect of confirming
[normal] this evolution
[normal]ary trend
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Consequently, prior to addressing questions of constitutional design for such a system of review, it is important to identify the 
[normal]constitutional
[normal] conditions that need to exist for a system of constitutional
[normal] review to function satis
[normal]factorily. It is these ‘
[normal]conditions’
[normal] or this constitutional environment that have the potential to affect
[normal] the principle of 
[normal]parliamentary sovereignty and to transform
[normal] the British constitution. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As mentioned above,
[normal] a certain constitutional envir
[normal]onment needs to exist
[normal] for a system of constitutional review to function and to be effective. 
[normal]However, to establish
[normal] 
[normal]this environment, some 
[normal]fundamental deci
[normal]sio
[normal]ns
[normal] on the character
[normal] and content of the 
[normal]codified constitution need to be made first
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The p[bold]rimacy of the codified constitution[bold]The adoption of a system of constitutional review r
[normal]aises
[normal] in turn
[normal] the question of the primacy
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]the future constitution
[normal]. 
[normal]It wo
[normal]uld be somewhat
[normal] impossible for
[normal] a 
[normal]full 
[normal]system of constitutional review 
[normal]to function w
[normal]e
[normal]re the codified constitution 
[normal]not granted
[normal] primacy over Acts of Parliament
[normal].
[normal] Only this higher status
[normal] 
[normal]would
[normal] give the necessary authority to the new constitution and to the system of constitutional review to
[normal] ensure
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]compliance
[normal] of Acts of Parliament
[normal] with the provisions of the constitution. Consequently, 
[normal]the new
[normal] codified
[normal] constitution 
[normal]would need to be placed 
[normal]at 
[normal]the 
[normal]apex of the constitutional
[normal] order 
[normal](or in jurisprudential parlance, 
[normal]at the top of the
[normal] ‘hierarchy of norms’
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A Bill of Rights?[bold]T
[normal]he second issue that should 
[normal]to be addressed
[normal] to create an effective
[normal] environment for constitutional review is th
[normal]e
[normal] adoption of 
[normal]a Bill of Rights.
[normal] 
[normal]While
[normal] constitutional review 
[normal]could exist and function without a
[normal] Bill of Rights
[normal], it
[normal] would be severely curtailed
[normal]. 
[normal]Traditionally, 
[normal]co
[normal]nstitutional review
[normal] 
[normal]ensures
[normal] the protection of
[normal] 
[normal]fundamental rights and freedoms. Indeed, w
[normal]ithout
[normal] a
[normal] Bill of R
[normal]ights
[normal], the courts 
[normal]would only be able to ensure
[normal] compliance with the
[normal] procedural requirements of the
[normal] legislative procedures or
[normal] the
[normal] 
[normal]constitutional
[normal] principles
[normal] clearly enounced in the constitution (such as 
[normal]the p
[normal]rinciple of 
[normal]in
[normal]dependence of t
[normal]he judiciary). This wo
[normal]uld establish
[normal] a very
[normal] narrow 
[normal]system of constitutional review and one that would 
[normal]tend to concentrate on the political system, its various mechanisms and the relationship and balance of 
[normal]power between Government, Parliament and Judiciary
[normal].
[normal] Traditionally, these 
[normal]areas are regulated efficiently by constitutional practices and conventions and although 
[normal]they would be 
[normal]codified in the new constitution, they may not ben
[normal]efit much from becoming the
[normal] focus of the new system of constitutional review. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Finally,
[normal] were the const
[normal]itution given primacy in the constitutional order and were a system of constitutional review 
[normal]be adopted, these would undermine
[normal] the main tenets of the principle of parliamentary sovereignty. Not only would the courts be empowered
[normal] to challenge the validity o
[normal]f
[normal] Act
[normal]s
[normal] of Parliament but
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]hey would no longer be held to have a somewhat inferior constitutional position to Parliament. The institutional balance inherent to the principle of parliamentary 
[normal]sovereignty would be compromised
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whatever the choices made with regard to the issu
[normal]es adumbrated above, these will
[normal] inform the design of the system of constitutional review. 
[normal]When designing a system of constitutional 
[normal]review, two main questions
[normal] need to be addressed: the 
[normal]choice of judicial structure and th
[normal]e type of judicial remedies
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Constitutional court v. ordinary courts[bold]There are two main options when deciding on th
[normal]e judicial structure 
[normal]appropriate for a system of
[normal] constitutional review
[normal]: a spe
[normal]cialized constitutional court 
[normal](e.g. the German, Italian and Spanish systems of constitutional review)
[normal] or a 
[normal]diffuse system of constitutional review
[normal] through the control of ordinary courts
[normal] (e.g. the system of 
[normal]constitutional review in the USA or in Greece). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The organisation of a 
[normal]‘
[normal]diffuse
[normal]’
[normal] system of constitutional review would not necessitate the creation of a new court and would only require
[normal] some adjustments to
[normal] the existing judicial processes
[normal] and court structure
[normal]. 
[normal]For instance, t
[normal]he constitutionality of an Act 
[normal]of Parliament relevant to the case could be challenged
[normal] in
[normal] all
[normal] ordinary litigations.
[normal]  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However
[normal], the majority of European countries resort
[normal] to constitutional courts. T
[normal]hese
[normal] specialized courts
[normal] 
[normal]concentrate 
[normal]all constitutional litigation
[normal] in one
[normal] 
[normal]court and
[normal] their
[normal] d
[normal]ecisions
[normal] 
[normal]often
[normal] have major poli
[normal]tical and societal implications. Consequently,
[normal] 
[normal]const
[normal]itutional courts can
[normal] attract deep and repe
[normal]ated criticisms. W
[normal]hen designing 
[normal]such a court
[normal], 
[normal]particular attention
[normal] need
[normal]s
[normal] to be given 
[normal]to
[normal] 
[normal]any aspect
[normal] that
[normal] may
[normal] foster legitimacy;
[normal] in particular both 
[normal]the m
[normal]embership and
[normal] appointment system
[normal] need
[normal]s
[normal] to be chosen
[normal] car
[normal]efully
[normal]. 
[normal]For instance, in the context of the UK judicial system, it
[normal] would be useful to move awa
[normal]y from the limitations of the
[normal] judicial appointm
[normal]e
[normal]nt system and allow
[normal] some
[normal] lay membe
[normal]rs with relevant knowledge (
[normal]e.g. 
[normal]political scientist or specialist in
[normal] ethics
[normal]) or professional experience (e
[normal].
[normal]g
[normal].
[normal] human rights campaigner of high standing)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Furth
[normal]ermore, the relationship of the constitutional
[normal] cou
[normal]rt with the ordinary courts would need to be or
[normal]ganized
[normal] carefully
[normal] to ensure that 
[normal]cases requiring
[normal] a constitutional ruling are referred
[normal] easily
[normal] to the constitutional court.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On balance, the choice of a diffuse system of constitutional review may suit the Brit
[normal]ish judicial system better. Also
[normal], there
[normal] has never been muc
[normal]h enthusiasm in the past for the creation of a
[normal] specialized public law court.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The remedies[bold]If 
[normal]the codifi
[normal]ed constitution were granted a higher status, then the court(s) should have the power
[normal] to strike down an unconstitutional Act of Parl
[normal]iament. 
[normal]In addition, the court(s) may need the power to modulate the eff
[normal]ect of their
[normal] ruling.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, t
[normal]o 
[normal]a
[normal]void the need for 
[normal]this type of 
[normal]modulation
[normal], 
[normal]the constitutionality of a b
[normal]ill
[normal] could be checked before coming
[normal] into
[normal] force. This 
[normal]system of 
[normal]pre-enactment
[normal] review 
[normal]would control
[normal] 
[normal]the bill 
[normal]once adopted
[normal] by Parliamen
[normal]t and be
[normal]fore receiving the
[normal] Royal Assent
[normal]. Accordingly, the court
[normal] would be able
[normal] able to ‘catch
[normal]’ unconstitutional provision
[normal]s
[normal] before they had any legal effect
[normal]. 
[normal]There would be
[normal] no need
[normal] to remedy
[normal] th
[normal]e
[normal] detrime
[normal]ntal impact
[normal] of an unconstitutional
[normal] 
[normal]Act of Parliament and no scope
[normal] for the modulation of the effect of a ruling of unconstitutionality
[normal].
[normal] However, the system of
[normal] pre-enactment review
[normal] has some 
[normal]known drawbacks. First, the control
[normal] is 
[normal]abstract and 
[normal]it is 
[normal]debatable 
[normal]whether any
[normal] court
[normal] in the circumstance
[normal]s
[normal] can really identify 
[normal]all possibl
[normal]e 
[normal]breaches of the constitution
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Also
[normal], 
[normal]this control 
[normal]occurs immediately after a bi
[normal]ll has been passed
[normal], when the political arguments for and against the text resounds around Parliament stil
[normal]l. 
[normal]In this context, it can be difficult for the
[normal] court
[normal] charged with this review not to be tainted by ‘political’ association. It would 
[normal]be 
[normal]all
[normal] the mor
[normal]e difficult if the
[normal] system of
[normal] pre-enactment review
[normal] is n
[normal]ot automatic but if it is
[normal] trigger
[normal]ed 
[normal]by 
[normal]any number of
[normal] 
[normal]elected representatives
[normal] 
[normal](e.g. the Prime Minister, the Speaker of the House of
[normal] Commons, a number of MPs) as is often the case 
[normal]for this type of revi
[normal]ew.
[normal] In fact, in many countries where it exists, pre-enactment review
[normal] is 
[normal]re
[normal]garded to be last obstacle 
[normal]the oppo
[normal]sition can put across the path of
[normal] bill
[normal]. 
[normal]In view of
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]rather
[normal] abstract nature of the litigation and the
[normal] politicized environment
[normal] in which it often operates, it 
[normal]is doubtful whether a system of pre-enactment review
[normal] would 
[normal]take root easily in the United Kingdom
